'''Francisco António Machado Mota de Castro Trincão''' ({{IPA|pt-PT|fɾɐ̃ˈsiʃku tɾĩˈkɐ̃w̃|lang}}; born 29 December 1999) is a Portuguese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for [[Primeira Liga]] club [[Sporting CP]] and the [[Portugal national football team|Portugal national team]].

He started his career with [[S.C. Braga B|Braga B]], making his debut with the [[S.C. Braga|first team]] in 2018 and winning the [[2019–20 Taça da Liga]] in his second season with the club. In January 2020, he signed with [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] for a reported €31 million fee, with the deal made effective in July. He then spent two years on loan, at [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] and [[Sporting CP]], joining the latter permanently in April 2023 and going on to make over 200 appearances and win two [[Primeira Liga]] titles and the [[2024–25 Taça de Portugal]].

Trincão represented [[Portugal national youth football team|Portugal]] at various youth levels, being part of the [[Portugal national under-19 football team|under-19 team]] that won the [[2018 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2018 European Championship]] where he was crowned top scorer. He made his senior international debut in 2020.

==Club career==
===Braga===
[[File:Francisco Trincão 2019 (cropped) 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Trincão with [[S.C. Braga|Braga]] in 2019]]
Born in [[Viana do Castelo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnportugal.iol.pt/p-s-para-seguir/para-seguir/trincao-ouro-vianense|title=Trincão, ouro vianense|trans-title=Trincão, gold from Viana|publisher=[[CNN Portugal|TVI 24]]|last=Travassos|first=Nuno|language=pt|date=23 February 2018|access-date=14 April 2026}}</ref> Trincão began his youth career with hometown club [[SC Vianense|Vianense]]. He also had a spell at [[FC Porto|Porto]] and two at [[S.C. Braga|Braga]], where he finished his development.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ominho.pt/francisco-trincao-do-sc-braga-eleito-atleta-revelacao-de-2018-em-viana-do-castelo/|title=Francisco Trincão, do SC Braga, eleito atleta revelação de 2018 em Viana do Castelo|trans-title=Francisco Trincão, of SC Braga, voted revelation athlete of 2019 in Viana do Castelo|newspaper=O Minho|language=pt|date=26 January 2019|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>

Trincão made his senior debut on 2 April 2016 for [[S.C. Braga B|Braga's reserves]] in [[Segunda Liga]], as an 81st-minute [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Carlos Fortes (footballer, born 1994)|Carlos Fortes]] in a 2–1 away loss against [[S.C. Freamunde|Freamunde]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://observador.pt/2018/07/27/trincao-o-mahrez-do-minho-que-da-nas-vistas-no-euro-de-sub-19-mas-precisou-de-autorizacao-dos-pais-para-viajar-com-o-braga/|title=Trincão. O Mahrez do Minho que dá nas vistas no Euro de Sub-19 mas precisou de autorização dos pais para viajar com o Braga|trans-title=Trincão. The Mahrez of the Minho who shines at the Under-19 Euros but needed parental authorisation to travel with Braga|newspaper=[[Observador]]|last=Ferreira Lima|first=Fábio|language=pt|date=27 July 2018|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref> He scored his first senior goal on 7 May 2017, but in a 2–3 home defeat to [[FC Porto B|Porto B]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/2--liga/detalhe/sp-braga-b-fc-porto-b-2-3-vitoria-garante-permanencia-aos-dragoes|title=Sp. Braga B-FC Porto B, 2–3: Vitória garante permanência aos dragões|trans-title=Sp. Braga B-FC Porto B, 2–3: Victory guarantees survival for the Dragons|newspaper=[[Record (Portuguese newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=7 May 2017|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref> He scored five times in [[2017–18 LigaPro|2017–18]], including twice on 1 October in a 5–4 home win over [[C.D. Nacional|Nacional]] for a first victory of the season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvi24.iol.pt/ii-liga/01-10-2017/chuva-de-golos-da-triunfo-do-braga-b-sobre-o-nacional|title=Chuva de golos dá triunfo do Braga B sobre o Nacional|trans-title=Rain of goals gives Braga B triumph over Nacional|publisher=TVI 24|language=pt|date=1 October 2017|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref> and signed a new five-year contract at the end.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/sp--braga/detalhe/trincao-renovou-por-cinco-epocas|title=Trincão renovou por cinco épocas|trans-title=Trincão renewed for five seasons|newspaper=Record|last=Monteiro|first=André|language=pt|date=6 July 2018|access-date=29 October 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029180432/https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/sp--braga/detalhe/trincao-renovou-por-cinco-epocas|archive-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>

On 28 December 2018, Trincão played his first competitive match with the first team in a 4–0 victory at [[Vitória F.C.|Vitória de Setúbal]] in the [[2018–19 Taça da Liga|group stage]] of the [[Taça da Liga]] where he replaced [[Fransérgio (footballer, born 1990)|Fransérgio]] in the 62nd minute.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dn.pt/lusa/comentario-braga-goleia-em-setubal-e-assegura-presenca-na-final-four-da-taca-da-liga-10379681.html|title=COMENTÁRIO: Braga goleia em Setúbal e assegura presença na 'final four' da Taça da Liga|trans-title=COMMENTARY: Braga rout in Setúbal and confirm presence in the League Cup's final four|newspaper=[[Diário de Notícias]]|language=pt|date=28 December 2018|access-date=10 April 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/braga/noticias/trincao-entre-a-estreia-no-braga-e-os-olhos-dos-gigantes-europeus-10382607.html|title=Trincão entre a estreia no Braga e os olhos dos gigantes europeus|trans-title=Trincão between Braga debut and eyes of European giants|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|last=Rocha|first=Pedro|language=pt|date=30 December 2018|access-date=11 April 2023}}</ref> Five days later, manager [[Abel Ferreira]] gave him a [[Primeira Liga]] debut when he came on for [[Dyego Sousa]] for the last four minutes of a home defeat of [[C.S. Marítimo|Marítimo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2019/01/02/desporto/noticia/sp-braga-bate-maritimo-fecha-ferida-luz-1856487|title=Sp. Braga bate Marítimo e fecha ferida da Luz|trans-title=Sp. Braga beat Marítimo and close wound from the ''Luz''|newspaper=[[Público (Portugal)|Público]]|language=pt|date=2 January 2019|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>

Trincão scored his first goal for Braga on 12 December 2019 in the last [[2019–20 UEFA Europa League|group-phase game]] of the [[UEFA Europa League]], also [[Assist (association football)|assisting]] in the 4–2 win at [[SK Slovan Bratislava|Slovan Bratislava]] as his team advanced in first place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://zap.aeiou.pt/slovan-2-4-braga-296987|title=Minhotos vencem grupo em grande estilo|trans-title=''Minhotos'' win group in some style|publisher=Zap|language=pt|date=12 December 2019|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The following 4 January, given a first league start by new coach [[Ruben Amorim]], he scored his first domestic league goal in a 7–1 away demolition of [[B-SAD]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ominho.pt/francisco-trincao-estreia-se-a-marcar-na-liga-de-futebol/|title=Francisco Trincão estreia-se a marcar na I Liga|trans-title=Francisco Trincão scores for the first time in I League|newspaper=O Minho|last=Silva|first=Fernando André|language=pt|date=5 January 2020|access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref> Three weeks later, he was a 50th-minute replacement for [[Galeno]] as the ''Arsenalistas'' won the [[2020 Taça da Liga final|league cup final]] against Porto at the [[Estádio Municipal de Braga]].<ref name=LC>{{cite web|url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/1458-late-ricardo-horta-strike-wins-the-taca-da-liga-for-braga|title=Late Ricardo Horta strike wins the Taça da Liga for Braga|publisher=PortuGOAL|last=Cole|first=Richard|date=25 January 2020|access-date=27 January 2020}}</ref>

===Barcelona===
On 31 January 2020, [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] announced the transfer of Trincão, initially effective on 1 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/transfer-deadline-day-latest-news-and-updates-from-premier-league-la-liga-serie-a-and-bundesliga/live/|title=Transfer deadline day: Latest news and updates from Premier League, La Liga, Serie A and Bundesliga|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|last=Gonzalez|first=Roger|date=31 January 2020|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> He signed a five-year contract for a €31 million fee, with a [[buyout clause]] of €500 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51323088|title=Barcelona to sign Francisco Trincao from Braga & Matheus Fernandes from Palmeiras|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=31 January 2020|access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref> He made his [[La Liga]] debut on 27 September, playing 12 minutes of the 4–0 home victory over [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/primera-division/barcelona-vs-villarreal/cronica/2020/09/27/5f70c84dca47412c2f8b45d1.html|title=Ansu Fati lidera el nuevo Barcelona|trans-title=Ansu Fati leads new Barcelona|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|last=Carnerero|first=Fernando|language=es|date=27 September 2020|access-date=27 September 2020}}</ref> He was handed his first start on 20 October in the 5–1 home rout of [[Ferencvárosi TC|Ferencváros]] in the [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League|group stage]] of the [[UEFA Champions League]], replacing [[Antoine Griezmann]] as the starting right winger and putting up a good performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/barcelona/2020/10/20/5f8f2525268e3e77058b45c0.html|title=Barcelona's starting XI vs Ferencvaros: Griezmann left on the bench|newspaper=Marca|date=20 October 2020|access-date=20 October 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfi.fr/en/wires/20201020-barcelona-start-afresh-five-goal-rout-ferencvaros|title=Barcelona start afresh with five-goal rout of Ferencvaros|publisher=[[Radio France Internationale]]|date=20 October 2020|access-date=20 October 2020}}</ref>

Trincão scored his first goal on 7 February 2021, closing the 3–2 away win against [[Real Betis]] in the domestic league.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/report?gameId=581983|title=Barcelona beat Real Betis with Messi, Trincao goals|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=7 February 2021|access-date=7 February 2021}}</ref> He added a brace the following weekend after assists by [[Ilaix Moriba]] and [[Lionel Messi]], helping the hosts to defeat [[Deportivo Alavés|Alavés]] 5–1.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/primera-division/barcelona-vs-alaves/cronica/2021/02/13/60280ee846163f66888b45c0.html|title=El Barça resuelve fácil y se centra en el PSG|trans-title=Barça get job done easily and focus on PSG|newspaper=Marca|last=Carnerero|first=Fernando|language=es|date=13 February 2021|access-date=13 February 2021}}</ref> He contributed five games as the side [[2021 Copa del Rey final|won]] the [[Copa del Rey]], totalling 42 overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/2107669/fc-barcelona-win-their-31st-copa-del-rey-title|title=FC Barcelona win their 31st Copa del Rey title|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=17 April 2021|access-date=18 November 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://es.besoccer.com/noticia/oficial-barca-cede-trincao-wolves-1013998|title=OFICIAL: el Barça cede a Trincao a los Wolves|trans-title=OFFICIAL: Barça loan Trincão to Wolves|publisher=[[BeSoccer]]|language=es|date=4 July 2021|access-date=18 November 2024}}</ref>

On 4 July 2021, Trincão joined [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] on a [[2021–22 Premier League|season]]-long loan, subject to medical and work permit and with an option to make the move permanent in the future;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20210704-wolves-complete-trincao-capture/|title=Wolves complete Trincao capture|publisher=Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|date=4 July 2021|access-date=4 July 2021}}</ref> he reunited with [[Pedro Neto]], with whom he had played as a child with Vianense and Braga.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ominho.pt/do-vianense-para-a-premier-league-trincao-e-neto-reunem-se-em-wolverhampton/|title=Do Vianense para a Premier League: Trincão e Neto reúnem-se em Wolverhampton|trans-title=From Vianense to the Premier League: Trincão and Neto reunite in Wolverhampton|newspaper=O Minho|language=pt|date=4 July 2021|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> He made his [[Premier League]] debut on 14 August, starting in a 1–0 loss away to [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/leicester-city-vs-wolverhampton-wanderers/report/446292|title=Leicester 1–0 Wolves: Jamie Vardy is the hero again as Foxes seal opening day Premier League win|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|last=Bate|first=Adam|date=14 August 2021|access-date=26 August 2021}}</ref> His first goal came ten days later, as a second-half substitute in a 4–0 victory at [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in the [[2021–22 EFL Cup|second round]] of the [[EFL Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58239476|title=Carabao Cup: Nottingham Forest 0–4 Wolverhampton Wanderers|publisher=BBC Sport|date=24 August 2021|access-date=24 August 2021}}</ref>

Trincão registered his first Premier League goal (also providing his first assist in the competition) in a 3–2 defeat at home to [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on 18 March 2022, having come on as a first-half substitute for injured [[Rúben Neves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60702578|title=Wolves 2–3 Leeds: Visitors fight back against 10 men to earn bruising win|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Stone|first=Simon|date=18 March 2022|access-date=19 March 2022}}</ref> He totalled 30 appearances during his tenure, starting in 16 but being only involved in four team goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2022/07/01/wolves-not-taking-up-25m-buy-option-on-francisco-trincao/|title=Wolves not taking up £25m buy option on Francisco Trincao|newspaper=[[Express & Star]]|last=Keen|first=Liam|date=1 July 2022|access-date=13 July 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stadiumastro.com/rencana/trincao-returns-barcelona-wolves-opt-against-triggering-option-217633|title=Trincao returns to Barcelona as Wolves opt against triggering option|publisher=Stadium Astro|last=Benson|first=Ryan|date=3 July 2022|access-date=13 July 2022}}</ref>

===Sporting CP===
On 13 July 2022, Trincão signed a one-year loan deal with [[Sporting CP]] for a €3 million fee, with a conditional €7 million obligation to buy 50% of his economic rights, with a reported buy-back clause between €20 and €25 million, depending on the moment it was exercised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sporting.pt/pt/noticias/futebol/equipa-principal/2022-07-13/francisco-trincao-vou-dar-tudo-pelo-sporting-cp|title=Francisco Trincão: "Vou dar tudo pelo Sporting CP"|trans-title=Francisco Trincão: "I will give everything for Sporting CP"|publisher=Sporting CP|language=pt|date=13 July 2022|access-date=13 July 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/football/first-team/news/2672239/trincao-loaned-to-sporting-clube-de-portugal|title=Trincão loaned to Sporting Clube de Portugal|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=13 July 2022|access-date=13 July 2022}}</ref> He made his league debut on 7 August in a 3–3 draw against his former club Braga.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abola.pt/nnh/2022-08-07/liga-sc-braga-empata-sporting-em-jogo-grande-com-seis-golos/952067|title=SC Braga empata Sporting em jogo grande com seis golos|trans-title=SC Braga draw Sporting in great match with six goals|newspaper=[[A Bola]]|language=pt|date=7 August 2022|access-date=9 September 2022|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220909185041/https://www.abola.pt/nnh/2022-08-07/liga-sc-braga-empata-sporting-em-jogo-grande-com-seis-golos/952067|archive-date=9 September 2022}}</ref> His first goal came exactly one month later, his team's second in the 3–0 away win over [[Eintracht Frankfurt]] in the [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League|Champions League group phase]], their first ever victory in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/2765-sporting-beat-eintracht-frankfurt-3-0-to-break-german-hoodoo|title=Sporting beat Eintracht Frankfurt 3–0 to break German hoodoo|publisher=PortuGOAL|last=Kundert|first=Tom|date=7 September 2022|access-date=9 September 2022}}</ref>

Over the following months, Trincão's performances declined and he began enduring a difficult [[2022–23 Primeira Liga|season]], with a lengthy scoring drought leading to many supporters demanding he be benched. Despite that, manager Amorim kept him in his starting eleven, and on 27 February 2023 he ran from one end of the penalty box to the other to score in the 2–0 home defeat of [[G.D. Estoril Praia|Estoril]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://observador.pt/2023/02/27/e-a-primeira-epoca-do-trincao-no-sporting-ele-parou-um-bocadinho-no-tempo-mas-o-talento-esta-la-e-so-olhar-para-o-edwards-diz-amorim/|title="É a primeira época do Trincão no Sporting, ele parou um bocadinho no tempo mas o talento está lá... É só olhar para o Edwards", diz Amorim|trans-title="This is Trincão's first season at Sporting, he stopped in time a little but the talent is there... Just have a look at Edwards", says Amorim|newspaper=Observador|last=Roseiro|first=Bruno|language=pt|date=27 February 2023|access-date=10 April 2023}}</ref> On 9 April, he netted a [[hat-trick]] in a 4–3 win at [[Casa Pia A.C.|Casa Pia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jn.pt/desporto/casa-pia-sporting-trincao-salva-leao-com-defesa-de-papel-16149685.html?target=conteudo_fechado|title=Casa Pia-Sporting: Trincão salva leão com defesa de papel|trans-title=Casa Pia-Sporting: Trincão saves lion with paper defence|newspaper=[[Jornal de Notícias]]|last=Antunes|first=Luís|language=pt|date=9 April 2023|access-date=10 April 2023}}</ref>

Trincão started [[2023–24 Primeira Liga|2023–24]] on the bench. However, after becoming a starter over [[Marcus Edwards]] in January 2024, he scored five goals in four league matches,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/taca-da-liga/sp-braga/a-haver-alteracao-no-sporting-passara-pelo-edwards-no-lugar-do-trincao#/|title="A haver alteração no Sporting, passará pelo Edwards no lugar do Trincão"|trans-title="Should Sporting make any changes, it will be Edwards for Trincão"|publisher=Mais Futebol|last=Castro|first=Ricardo Jorge|language=pt|date=22 January 2024|access-date=30 January 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/6790062124/francisco-trincao-como-nunca-se-viu-e-marselha-caiu-por-terra/|title=Francisco Trincão como nunca se viu e Marselha caiu por terra|trans-title=Francisco Trincão like you've never seen him and Marseille brought to their knees|newspaper=O Jogo|language=pt|date=25 January 2024|access-date=30 January 2024}}</ref> including a brace in a 8–0 home rout of Casa Pia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jn.pt/7879400429/sporting-com-todo-o-gas-veja-os-seis-golos-ao-casa-pia/|title=Sporting goleia o Casa Pia por 8–0. Veja os golos|trans-title=Sporting thrash Casa Pia 8–0. Watch the goals|newspaper=Jornal de Notícias|last=Pedrosa Costa|first=Eduardo|language=pt|date=29 January 2024|access-date=30 January 2024}}</ref> Having cemented his role up front alongside [[Pedro Gonçalves]] and [[Viktor Gyökeres]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/sporting/figuras/de-amorim-a-viktor-as-figuras-do-sporting-campeao|title=De Amorim a Viktor: as figuras do Sporting campeão|trans-title=From Amorim to Viktor: the stars of champions Sporting|publisher=Mais Futebol|last=Rodrigues|first=Berta|language=pt|date=5 May 2024|access-date=9 January 2025}}</ref> he added four more until the end of the campaign as Sporting won its 20th league, totalling 1,695 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvi.iol.pt/noticias/liga/sporting/sporting-29-campeoes-entre-eles-quatro-guarda-redes-e-um-jogador-despromovido|title=Sporting: 29 campeões, entre eles quatro guarda-redes e um jogador... despromovido|trans-title=Sporting: 29 champions, including four goalkeepers and a... relegated player|publisher=[[Televisão Independente]]|language=pt|date=19 May 2024|access-date=6 November 2024}}</ref>

On 11 January 2025, Trincão was the only player to miss his attempt in the 7–6 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] loss against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in the [[2025 Taça da Liga final|League Cup final]] in [[Leiria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/4432-benfica-beat-sporting-cp-on-penalties-to-claim-the-taca-da-liga|title=Benfica beat Sporting CP on penalties to claim the Taça da Liga|publisher=PortuGOAL|last=Marshall|first=Matthew|date=11 January 2025|access-date=13 January 2025}}</ref> On 10 May, against the same opposition but in the [[Derby de Lisboa]], he opened an eventual 1–1 away draw<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jn.pt/6763336238/leao-ganha-batalha-de-nervos-e-fica-perto-do-bicampeonato/|title=Leão ganha batalha de nervos e fica perto do bicampeonato|trans-title=Lion wins war of nerves and is close to back-to-back championship|newspaper=Jornal de Notícias|last=Farinha|first=Rui|language=pt|date=10 May 2025|access-date=18 May 2025}}</ref> and, again, finished [[2024–25 Primeira Liga|the season]] with nine goals to claim a national championship while taking part in all 34 fixtures and providing a league-best 14 assists.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://observador.pt/2025/05/17/quem-sao-os-34-novos-campeoes-pelo-sporting-em-2024-25-e-o-que-fizeram-ao-longo-da-epoca/|title=Quem são os 34 novos campeões pelo Sporting em 2024/25 (e o que fizeram ao longo da época)|trans-title=Who are the 34 new champions for Sporting in 2024/25 (and what did they do throughout the season)|newspaper=Observador|last=Roseiro|first=Bruno|language=pt|date=17 May 2025|access-date=18 May 2025}}</ref>

Trincão scored his first brace in the Champions League on 18 September 2025, also being named [[player of the match]] in the 4–1 home victory over [[FC Kairat|Kairat]] in the [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League|league phase]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/sporting/champions/champions-trincao-eleito-o-homem-do-jogo|title=Champions: Trincão eleito o homem do jogo|trans-title=Champions League: Trincão voted man of the match|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=18 September 2025|access-date=22 September 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
In July 2018, Trincão was a member of the [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal team]] which won the [[UEFA European Under-19 Championship]] beating [[Italy national under-19 football team|Italy]] 4–3 after [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]]; he scored once in the match in [[Seinäjoki]], Finland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/internacional/europeu-sub-19/conheca-os-20-mais-um-campeoes-europeus-de-sub-19|title=Conheça os 20 (mais um) campeões europeus de sub-19|trans-title=Meet the 20 (plus one) under-19 European champions|publisher=Mais Futebol|last=Esteves|first=Adérito|language=pt|date=30 July 2018|access-date=6 November 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pt.uefa.com/under19/news/0257-0dee66014813-dfafa0e3dfa4-1000--por-onde-andam-os-vencedores-do-euro-sub-19-por-portugal/|title=Por onde andam os vencedores do EURO Sub-19 por Portugal?|trans-title=Where are the Under-19 EURO winners for Portugal?|publisher=UEFA|language=pt|date=29 January 2019|access-date=6 November 2024}}</ref> Along with teammate [[Jota (footballer, born March 1999)|Jota]], he finished joint top scorer in the tournament with five goals, his others being braces against [[Norway national under-19 football team|Norway]] in the first group fixture and [[Ukraine national under-19 football team|Ukraine]] in a 5–0 semi-final rout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11454150/domingos-quina-moise-kean-joao-filipe-impress-at-under-19-euros|title=Domingos Quina, Moise Kean, Joao Filipe impress at Under-19 Euros|publisher=Sky Sports|last=Walker-Roberts|first=James|date=30 July 2018|access-date=30 July 2018}}</ref> At the [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] in Poland he played all three games and scored the only goal of the opening win against [[South Korea national under-20 football team|South Korea]], though [[Portugal national under-20 football team|his side]] did not advance from the group.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://observador.pt/2019/05/25/portugal-vence-coreia-do-sul-na-estreia-no-mundial-sub-20-com-golo-de-trincao/|title=Portugal vence Coreia do Sul na estreia no Mundial Sub-20 com golo de Trincão|trans-title=Portugal beat South Korea in opening game of the Under-20 World Cup with goal by Trincão|newspaper=Observador|last=Fernandes|first=Mariana|language=pt|date=25 May 2019|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>

Trincão won his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] at [[Portugal national under-21 football team|under-21 level]] on 5 September 2019, scoring once and being involved in two other goals in the 4–0 win over [[Gibraltar national under-21 football team|Gibraltar]] for the [[2021 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2021 European Championship]] [[2021 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|qualifiers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/selecao/trincao/euro-sub-21-portugal-gibraltar-4-0-destaques|title=Euro Sub-21: Portugal-Gibraltar, 4–0 (destaques)|trans-title=Under-21 Euro: Portugal-Gibraltar, 4–0 (highlights)|publisher=Mais Futebol|last=Gouveia|first=Ricardo|language=pt|date=5 September 2019|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/selecoes/sub21/detalhe/trincao-e-o-golo-frente-a-gibraltar-tentei-a-minha-sorte-e-correu-bem|title=Trincão e o golo frente a Gibraltar: "Tentei a minha sorte e correu bem"|trans-title=Trincão and the goal against Gibraltar: "I tried my luck and it went well"|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=6 September 2019|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> He helped the Portuguese to a runners-up finish at the finals in Hungary and Slovenia, scoring a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] in a 2–0 group defeat of [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12016/12259341/portugal-u21s-2-0-england-u21s-dany-mota-trincao-leave-young-lions-euro-u21-championship-hopes-hanging-by-thread|title=Portugal U21s 2–0 England U21s: Dany Mota, Trincao leave Young Lions' Euro U21 Championship hopes hanging by thread|publisher=Sky Sports|last=Walker|first=Ron|date=29 March 2021|access-date=8 June 2021}}</ref>

===Senior===
[[File:Francisco Trincão USMNT v Portugal Mar 31 2026-91.jpg|thumb|upright|Trincão in action for [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in March 2026]]
In August 2020, Trincão had his first [[Portugal national football team|senior]] call-up for [[UEFA Nations League]] matches against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] and [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] the following month.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abola.pt/nnh/2020-08-24/selecao-rui-silva-e-trincao-em-estreia-absoluta-nos-convocados/858161|title=Rui Silva e Trincão em estreia absoluta nos convocados|trans-title=Rui Silva and Trincão called up for the very first time|newspaper=A Bola|language=pt|date=24 August 2020|access-date=24 August 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201101161713/https://www.abola.pt/nnh/2020-08-24/selecao-rui-silva-e-trincao-em-estreia-absoluta-nos-convocados/858161|archive-date=1 November 2020}}</ref> He made his debut on 5 September, replacing [[Bernardo Silva]] in the 78th minute of a 4–1 home victory over the former.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/news/0261-104df9ab20e7-ebd4defbd745-1000--portugal-4-1-croatia-holders-ease-to-emphatic-victory/|title=Portugal 4–1 Croatia: Holders ease to emphatic victory|publisher=UEFA|date=5 September 2020|access-date=6 September 2020}}</ref>

Trincão was named in a preliminary 55-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/selecoes/detalhe/cmtv-revela-lista-de-pre-convocados-para-o-mundial2022-conheca-todos-os-nomes?ref=HP_DestaquesPrincipais|title=A lista de pré-convocados da Seleção para o Mundial'2022: conheça todos os nomes|trans-title=The pre-selected for the 2022 World Cup: know all the names|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=23 October 2022|access-date=31 October 2022}}</ref> He did not make the final cut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/mundial/artigos/os-26-convocados-de-portugal-para-o-mundial2022|title=Os 26 convocados de Portugal: Gonçalo Ramos, António Silva, Otávio e Matheus Nunes chamados|trans-title=Portugal select 26: Gonçalo Ramos, António Silva, Otávio and Matheus Nunes called|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|language=pt|date=10 November 2022|access-date=9 January 2025}}</ref>

In October 2024, courtesy of his Sporting performances, Trincão was called by new manager [[Roberto Martinez]] for upcoming [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League|2024–25 Nations League]] matches. He played 26 minutes in the 3–1 win against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] in [[Warsaw]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/selecao/francisco-trincao/trincao-volta-a-jogar-pela-selecao-mais-de-tres-anos-depois|title=Trincão volta a jogar pela Seleção mais de três anos depois|trans-title=Trincão plays for the national team again more than three years later|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=12 October 2024|access-date=29 December 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvi.iol.pt/noticias/selecao/francisco-trincao/trincao-volta-a-jogar-pela-selecao-mais-de-tres-anos-depois|title=Trincão volta a jogar pela Seleção mais de três anos depois|trans-title=Trincão for the national team again more than three years later|publisher=Televisão Independente|language=pt|date=12 October 2024|access-date=29 December 2024}}</ref>

Trincão scored his first goals for Portugal on 23 March 2025, grabbing a brace in a 5–2 victory over [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] in the Nations League quarter-finals (5–3 on aggregate) after coming on for [[Diogo Dalot]] late into the second half.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2025/03/23/desporto/cronica_de_jogo/seleccao-errou-trincao-nao-portugal-vai-meiafinal-liga-nacoes-2127077|title=A selecção errou, Trincão não. Portugal vai à meia-final da Liga das Nações|trans-title=The national team made mistakes, Trincão did not. Portugal go to Nations League semi-finals|newspaper=Público|last=Cardoso Oliveira|first=Diogo|language=pt|date=23 March 2025|access-date=23 March 2025}}</ref> He was selected for [[2025 UEFA Nations League Finals|the finals]] in Germany,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fpf.pt/pt/News/Todas-as-notícias/Notícia/news/50645|title=Convocatória para Liga das Nações divulgada|trans-title=Nations League squad announced|publisher=[[Portuguese Football Federation]]|language=pt|date=20 May 2025|access-date=14 June 2025}}</ref> starting the 2–1 semi-final defeat of [[Germany national football team|the hosts]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cj6rw18xk1yt|title=Germany 1–2 Portugal|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Emons|first=Michael|date=4 June 2025|access-date=9 June 2025}}</ref> and being unused in the [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] win against [[Spain national football team|Spain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cvgqzyl24j4t|title=Portugal 2–2 Spain (5–3 after pens)|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Salley|first=Emily|date=8 June 2025|access-date=9 June 2025}}</ref>

Trincão was included in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026 World Cup]] squad.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/2026/05/19/the-reason-portugal-called-up-4-goalkeepers-for-world-cup-reason-to-fret-for-cristiano-ronaldo-fans.html|title=The reason Portugal called up 4 goalkeepers for World Cup: No reason to fret for Cristiano Ronaldo fans|newspaper=Marca|first=Matias|last=Wodner|date=19 May 2026|access-date=1 June 2026}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Trincão is a versatile and technical [[right winger]], adept at adapting to various attacking roles. He frequently drifts centrally in possession, creating space for overlapping teammates with tactical intelligence. Known for his ball control, maneuverability in tight spaces and a strong left foot, he excels in one-on-one situations, precise dribbling and incisive passing.<ref name=TFA>{{cite web|url=https://totalfootballanalysis.com/player-analysis/francisco-trincao-201920-scout-report-tactical-analysis-tactics|title=Francisco Trincão 2019/20 – scouting report|publisher=Total Football Analysis|last=Martin|first=Scott|date=28 March 2020|access-date=29 December 2024}}</ref><ref name=FP>{{cite web|url=https://fairplay.pt/futebol/espanha/la-liga-scouting-12-francisco-trincao-fc-barcelona/|title=La Liga Scouting #12 – Francisco Trincão (FC Barcelona)|publisher=Fair Play|last=Dias|first=Bruno|language=pt|date=16 April 2020|access-date=29 December 2024}}</ref><ref name=TS>{{cite web|url=https://targetscouting.com/2020/04/21/francisco-trincao-2/|title=Francisco Trincão – Player report|publisher=Target Scouting|last=Brace|first=Emiraldo|date=21 April 2020|access-date=29 December 2024}}</ref>

Trincão plays a key role in build-up play through quick combinations and penetrating passes. Despite being left-footed, he uses the outside of his foot creatively and delivers accurate crosses, making him a consistent wide-area threat. Defensively, he is active in pressing and transitions, leveraging his dynamic movement, spatial awareness and adaptability to succeed in high-intensity, possession-focused systems.<ref name=TFA/><ref name=FP/><ref name=TS/>

